Transit Oriented Development in Essex-Hudson Counties

By Stephanie Onuaja

September 9, 2022

Analyzing Transit Oriented Development Potential in Essex-Hudson, NJ

Taking the combined geographies of Essex and Hudson Counties, this analysis aims to assess the potential for transit-oriented development around the Hudson–Bergen Light Rail and Newark City Subway lines. It hopes to evaluate the indicators suggestive of that potential identified between 2009 to 2019. Furthermore, it intends to contrast discoveries in non-TOD areas to grasp the perceived value of TOD; and to potentially understand gaps in transport connectivity in the municipalities within these northern New Jersey counties.

Data Sources

The demographic and transit data used for this analysis were from the following sources:

  • American Community Survey 5-Year Estimates (2009 & 2019)
  • New Jersey Geographic Information Network

tracts09 <-

         MaleBachelors = B15001_009,

tracts09 <-

         pctBlack = ifelse(TotalPop > 0, Blacks / TotalPop, 0),
         pctBachelors = ifelse(TotalPop > 0, ((FemaleBachelors + MaleBachelors) / TotalPop), 0),

0.2 Spatial Operations

buffer <- filter(LRBuffers, Legend=="Unioned Buffer")
sf::sf_use_s2(FALSE)
# Spatial clipping at unioned buffer boundaries
clip <- 
  st_intersection(buffer, tracts09) %>%
  dplyr::select(TotalPop) %>%
  mutate(Selection_Type = "Clip") 

# Spatial selection on polygons touching the buffer
selection <- 
  tracts09[buffer,] %>%
  dplyr::select(TotalPop) %>%
  mutate(Selection_Type = "Spatial Selection")

# Spatial intersection with on polygon centroids
selectCentroids <-
  st_centroid(tracts09)[buffer,] %>%
  st_drop_geometry() %>%
  left_join(., dplyr::select(tracts09, GEOID), by = "GEOID") %>%
  st_sf() %>%
  dplyr::select(TotalPop) %>%
  mutate(Selection_Type = "Select by Centroids")

0.4 TOD Indicator Plots

The TOD indicator plots and tables supplement our understanding of the demographic changes that may not have been legible in the indicator maps alone.

Between 2009 and 2019, areas around transit gained more residents with bachelor’s degrees and experienced increases in median rent and income. In the TOD areas, the Black population and poverty rates decreased.

Moreover, non-TOD areas saw a decline in the White and Black populations and bachelor’s degree holders, while poverty rates, rent, and income increased.


allTracts.Summary <- 
  st_drop_geometry(allTracts.group) %>%
  group_by(year, TOD) %>%
  summarize(Rent = mean(MedRent, na.rm = T),
            HHIncome = mean(MedHHInc, na.rm = T),
            Population = mean(TotalPop, na.rm = T),
            Pct_White = mean(pctWhite, na.rm = T),
            Pct_Black = mean(pctBlack, na.rm = T),
            Pct_Bach = mean(pctBachelors, na.rm = T),
            Pct_Poverty = mean(pctPoverty, na.rm = T))

allTracts.Summary %>%
  gather(Variable, Value, -year, -TOD) %>%
  ggplot(aes(year, Value, fill = TOD)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "dodge") +
  facet_wrap(~Variable, scales = "free", ncol=7) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("#7fcdbb","#1d91c0")) +

0.5 TOD Indicator Tables

The values in the tables suggest that:

  • Household income has increased by 29 % in TOD areas, and 21 % in non-TOD areas
  • Rent has increased by 27 % in TOD areas, and 33 % in non-TOD areas
  • Percent Black population decreased by 17 % in TOD areas, and 27 % in non-TOD areas
  • Percent White population did not change TOD areas, and decreased by 17 % in non-TOD areas
  • Percent of bachelor holders increased by 11 % in TOD areas, and decreased by 21 % in non-TOD areas
  • Percentage Poverty decreased by 3% in TOD areas, and increased by 12 % in non-TOD areas
  • Total Population increased by 9% in TOD areas, and 2% in non-TOD areas

Conclusions

Over the 10-year period, TOD and non-TOD areas in Essex-Hudson have experienced vast demographic changes. While we can identify these changes, there is a gap in the context to suggest any causation.

While TOD areas have incentivized the increase in residents with higher educational levels and income, as well as an increase in property values; we cannot make absolute conclusions on the perceived valorization of transit-oriented development. There may be residents who may value the benefits of living TOD area but cannot afford the cost of living.

When comparing this to the changes in non-TOD areas, it is interesting that rental costs have increased at a higher level than in TOD areas, and on average become more expensive further away from transit. It is important to consider this coupled with the 12 % increase in poverty levels in non-TOD areas. As the demographics in the area continue to transform, it is imperative that the most vulnerable residents in this changing context must be protected. Action should be taken to preserve affordability in both TOD and non- TOD areas and accessibility to TOD areas for lower-income residents.

More research is needed to understand the shifting demographics by adding layers such as job inflow and outflow, access to healthy food options, income classes, schools, and additional transit data to supplement the result and analysis.
